	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I'm bringing this back from the dead because I've been doing some maintenance on my consoles... I added composite output to my SMS III, converted my Atari 2600 to NTSC (the guide I used for composite video resulted in colors that were too saturated so I reverted to RF), and now I feel like making my NES output NTSC video again.
<br />
<br />I found a <a href="http://www.nesarchive.net/forum/index.php?topic=11434.0" class="postlink">page in (bad) portuguese</a> that explains the whole procedure. It shows exactly what traces have to be reconnected and says that you have to replace the crystal with a 21.47727 MHz one. Thing is I can't find this crystal anywhere, but I have a 3.579545 MHz one (the same kind I used to make my Atari NTSC). IIRC, the 21.47727 MHz are divided to achieve the 3.579545 used in NTSC video, right? Does this mean that somehow I can bypass the divider and use my 3.579545 crystal?
<br />
<br />Please hardware gurus, let me know if you think this is possible and how.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

